otion all unions are urged to\nI take out membership in the Workers\nKrliiratinn Bureau of the AFL to Dre\nEducation Bureau ol tue m i. to pr\npare for a mid-winter institute at Great\nBalle\n1 la,1Sl\nJ\nOn motion a committee of me was\nappointed to attend the open meeting\nto protest installation of parking meters\nat the Civic Center on September Lth\nand parallel parking.\nJohn Dusak, E. R. Richards, A. J.\nDuley, Ray Rebal and Leo Stewart were\nappointed on this committee,\nJOHN EVANKO, Jr., Secy. j\nWASHINGTON. (FP) The stamp j\nof approval of the AFL was placed on\nthe Murray-Wagner full employment\nbill by President William Green be\nfore the Senate banking and currency\nOthers who testified in\nGood and Welfare\nI\n\n11\n\u00ee\ni M|H| i t j I\ncommittee,\nfavor of the bill included Pres. John L.\nLewis of United Mine orkers (unaffili\nated), Sec. of Commerce Henry A. Wal\nlace, Sec. of Labor Lewis B. Schwellen\nhach and a number of conservative\nt hankers and merchandisers. Pres. Ira\nI Mosher of the National Association of\nI Manufacturers and few other diehards\nI opposed the measure.\n\u00bb.\u2022ll\u25a0\"\u25a0l.\u25a0n\nn\nSWISS CREAMERY\nAND\nCHEESE FACTORY\nERNEST EGGER, Prop.\nDealer In Peed, Grain, Coal\u2014\nJ. L Case Machinery\nWholesale and Retail\nCHEESE AND BI TTER\nALPINE DAIRY PRODUCTS\n\n\nWhitehall, Montana\n\nUNIONS REQUESTED\nTO INVESTIGATE\nUNEMPLOYMENT TAX\nFollowing resolutions, two of which\ndeal with taxes ol the Unemployment\nCompensation Act and the other one\nabout the creation of Missouri Valley\nAuthority were submitted to the recent\nconvention of the Montana State Feder\nation of Labor held at Billings, Mont\nj by the Cascade County Trades Labor\nAssembly. The Cascade county assembly\nrequ\u00e9sts that all unions of Montana\nhp mmhlMonS\nalso adopt tnese resolutions.\nm _\ntween Unemployment Compensation\nCommission and Central Labor Coun\ncils\nResolution to arrange meetings be\nWHEREAS, The purpose of these\nj meetings is to impress the Commission\nj aIH ac J v is\u00abjry council with the import\nante of changing the tax structure of\nthe Unemployment Compensation Act\nsu that those employers whose account\nindicates that they are less responsi\n1\nWHEREAS, Employer groups have\nhad numerous meetings with the Un\nemployment Compensation Commission\nand advisory council, and\nbile for unemployment than other em\nployers, may get a tax reduction (ex\nperience rating) and\nWHEREAS, Experience rating in\nevitably means season classification of\nworkers, and\nWHEREAS, Season classification of\nworkers in Montana would disqualify\napproximately 35 per cent of the cov\nered workers (building and construc\ntion trades, and all workers whose em\nployment is dependable upon suitable\nweather in which to work) except dur\nJ n g the season that the type of work\nc\n1 they follow is normal!} operating, anti,\nWHEREAS, Unemployment Compen\n\nsation was originally designed to tide\nperiods,\n\ni\nI\n_ ,i lp\narrange meetings in caul of the u un\nties where there is an active central\nnth the Montana State Un\nit seas\nworkers over these\nr therefore he it\nRESOLVED, That we instruct the\npresident and executive board of the\ni Montana State Federation of Labor to\n1\nRESOLVED. That we oppose t*\npenence Rating until the U. C. Act is\nliberalized m conformity with our\ncouncil,\nemployment Compensation Commission\nso that as many representatives of labor\nas possible may attend these meetings\nexpress their views on Experience\nRating, Seasonal Classification, In\ncreased Benefits and labors views\nstrengthening instead\nto\ngeneral\nweakening the act, and be it further\nj views, and the reserve fund is protect\nj e( along the lines of the New York Act.\ni\nraise Unemployment\n.01) a week and extend\nj Benefits to\nduration of benefits to 26 weeks,\nWHEREAS. With an anticipated re\nResolution to\nserve fund <\u00bbf more than twenty million\nj dollars in the Unemployment Compen\nit is expected\nj sation fund by the time our next legis\nj t at there will be a drive on by the re\nactionary forces of the state to weaken\nthe act by reducing the tax on the cm\nployer, and\nWHEREAS. To weake\nlative s\nnon convenes\nmaking i\n{lack D f sufficient tax would be to rob\ntlie act by\niads on the reserves through\nthe insured worker of some of the hene\nfj t low enjoyed, and\nWHEREAS, Most of the states im\nmediately surrounding Montana have\nstrengthened their Unemployment Uom\npmsatjon act to lltc extent that benefits\npaid are much more liberal than those\npa id in Montana and\n1,1 \"Juumiui,\nWHEREAS, The financial condition\nof the Montana Unemployment Com\npensation fund should give evidence\n,hat the benefits paid under the act can\n\n)c liberalized rather than reduced, and\nWHKRKAS, Most employers answer\ning a questionairc sent out' by the Un\nemployment Compensation Commission\nare in agreement that the benefits under\ntlie act should be increased, now there-1\nf ore )e it\n\nRESOLVED, That we instruct our]\npresident and executive board to pre\npare and submit amendments to the\nUnemployment Compensation Act that\nLjn raise t le \u201elaxyuim weekly benefit\ntwenty-five dollars ($25.00) and ex\ntend the duration of benefits to twenty\nsix (26) weeks and be it further\nRESOLVED, That the method of de\n\ntermilling the amount of weekly benefit\ndu an unemployed worker he increased\nrtmi f our pcr cent of the highest quar\nj crs ea rnincs to five per cent of the\nf\nearnings of the highest quarter.\n_\nu w a\nResolutions on Missouri Valley Au\nthority\nWHEREAS, Business, industry,\nf arniers an( j workers of the state corn\np r j s j n g the Tennessee Valley are unani\nmous j n their praise of the benefits to\nth e entire area, through thfe develop\nmnt G f JVA, and\nWHEREAS, A bill has been intro\nuce( i j n Congress which would set up\na Missouri Valley Authority patterned\nafter TV A, and\nWHEREAS, The states comprising\n,j le \\ji ssour j Valley drainage area have\nI\nfar greater natural resources than any\nof the states comprising the TVA, and\nthe development of these natural re\nsources would open new frontiers of\ncommerce, industry and agriculture\nwhich would give employment to our\nreturning soldiers, and\nWHEREAS, Opposition to this na\ntional project has developed from a\ngroup whom we believe are influenced\nby the great power and other selfish\ncorporate interests desirous of monopo\nlistic. control of onr great streams, pow\ner sites and other natural resources, and\nwhich in case of the irrigation dam at\nTosten, Montana, gives us foundation\nfur this belief; also the fact that hydro\nelectric power sites are and have been\nunder monopolistic control, thereby de\npriving the people of full use and bene\nfit of these must important natural re\nsources, and\nWHEREAS, It is our considered\nopinion that the interests of irrigation,\nnavigation, flood control and power dc\nvelopmcnt can be best served by the\nestablishment of one authority with full\nauthority to develop and preserve the\npeople*\u00bb interests; therefore be it\nKtSULV ED, That we urge and re\nquest Congress to establish a Missouri\nValley Authority patterned after the\nTennessee Valley Authority, designed\nfor \"the definite purpose of a co-ordi\nnated development of the natural re\nsources of the Missouri Valley area for\nthe benefit of all the people, and be it\nfurther\nRESOLVED, That copies of this\nresolution be forwarded our two Sena\ntors and Congressmen, and President\nTruman, and James D. Graham, presi\ndent of Montana State Federation of\nLabe., with the request they put all\ntheir efforts behind the enactment of\nMVA legislation.\nMINE FINANCE PU I\nHAS MUCH AMBITION\nA bill has been introduced in Con\nby (Congressman Clair \u00a3ngle of\ngress\nCalifornia to broaden and extend the\nprovisions of the reconstruction finance\ncorporation act which are applicable to\nloans for the development of mineral\ndeposits.\nThe new bill, which superceds HR\n1768, authorizes the RFC to make loans\nfor the purpose, of making accessible,\nexamining or developing mine, placer\nor quarry workings mining, milling,\nsmelting, or otherwise treating ores;\nquarrying and preparing of quarry\nproducts for the markets maintenance\nnd rehabilitation of gold mines that\nwere closed or curtailed by WLB limi\ntation order L-208 or other government\nrestrictions.\nUnder existing law the original loan\nfor mineral development may not\nceed $20,000, hut an additional loan of\nlike amount may he made later if ini\ntial development justifies it.\nCongressman. Engle's plan, the RFC is\nauthorized to loan the actual amount of\nmoney required to put the property in\noperation,\ntana L__\ni the Senate. (It might break to govern\n(ment to put some prospective mines\niperation.)\u2014The Wallace\n\norders\nex\nUnder\nSenator Murray of Mon\nhas introduced an identical bill in\nj\nin\nsuccessful\nMiner.\nJOHN O'DONNELL IS\nNEW FIRE CHIEF\nNews of the appointment of John\nO'Donnell as chief of the* Butte fire de\npartment was well received by the peo\nple of Butte and the unions. Mr. O'Don\nnell, a veteran of World War I, has a\nhost of friends in this city who wish\nI him well in his new position.\nI O'Donnell was appointed assistant chief\nI Sept. 6, 1944, and has been acting chief\nince that timc\nn McCarth a member o{ the de\nI partment s j nce Nov. 18. 1942, was named\nassistant chief.\nChief\n_\nLEGAL NOTICES\nNOTICE TO CREDITORS\nc of EDWARD J. GLENNON. Deceased\nby the undersigned\nE-t\nNotice is hereby glv\noi Edward\nGlennon, deceased, to the creditors of and\nall persons having claims against the said\ndeceased, to exhibit them, with the neces\nvouchers, withl\nfirst publication of this notice to the said\nadministrator at 314 Silver Bow Block, Butte.\nMontana, the same being the place for the\nsaction of the business of said estate,\nIn the County of Sllv\n(ana.\nsary\nfour months alter the\n1\nBow. State of Mon\nMARY GLENNOK,\nAdministratrix of the Estate of Edward J\nGlennon, Deceased.\nDated Butte. Montana, this 4th day of Sep\ntember, 1945\nFirst Publication September 6. 1945\u20144T\nNOTICE OF \u00ab5*1 p OF \u00bbfat AND\nPERSONAL PROPERTY\nin the District Court of the Second Judicial\nDistrict of the state of Montana, in and\nIn uJttToTth/ \u00c4 August Abra\nhamson, Deceased,\nnotice is hereby given; That in pur\nsuance of an order of the District Court of\nthe Second Judicial District of the state of\nu d n u m. \u00ab\"IS? i.V d\"'\"?\nSeptember, 1945 In Hie above-entitled estate,\nundersigned the administrator of the\nabove-entitled estate, will sell at private sale\nto the highest bidder, tor cash, and subject\nto confirmation by said court, all the right,\nce^ed^nlThls' St M ?aU TaTn\u00e4V^lolloT.\ning real and personal property situated\nS d 2S b 5T\u00ef\u00ef^oi^\u00ef^\"%rl\u00ee? Ml PBrttCU\nd) Lot 3 i-n Block 4 of the Crosbv\nAddition to the City of Butte, in silver\nBow County, Montana, according to the\nofficial plat and\nRgcorder'o^BUv f thC County clerk and\nwl th frame dwelling house thereon, also\nknown as 2616 Locust street. Butte, an\nr Bo Monarch rang,;\ni Oakland gas heater; i kitchen table\nt b a 3 l k c \u00c4\u00c4' n\nbed: 1 dresser; and one small table.\n1, \u00bb'J? 8 \"VJf 'V 1 1 18\nleft In the office of the Public Administrator\nof Silver Bow County. Montana, on the third\ni\n(ey thereof\nBow County, Montana.\ncouch; 1\nJ \u00ee!i ve L\u2122. w\ndelivered to the administrator personally, or\nmay be filed in the affice of the c,erk of\nthe above-entitled court, at any time after\nthe rust publication o( this notice and before\nsa j,.\nThe sale will be made on\nda y of September, 1945\nDated this 1st day\nafter the 24th\nSeptPmHnv ir/tt\nMARY WALSH,\nAs administratrix of the Estate of August\nAbrahamson, deceased.\nFirst Fublicati\nSeptember 6. 1945\u20142T\nNo. 11653\nORDER TO SHOW CAUSE WHY\nAN ORDER OF SALE OF REAL\nESTATE SHOULD NOT BE\n