oughran, Lowe, McCherry, McDan\nnels, McGreevey, Martin, Marty, Mayo,\nMoen, Nelson, O'Connell, Oliver, Pad\nhury, Page, Parker (Wibaux), Parker,\n(Cascade), Patterson, Phillips, Pierce.\nRasmussen, Scofield, Simpson, Stout.\nTabor, Taylor, Teigen, Thomas, Tier\nney, Toole, Udin, Williams, Wilson.\nVoting no\u2014Helding.\nAbsent not voting\u2014Antrim, Arm\nstrong, Banka, Blenker, Bovey, O'Con\nnor, Doughtery, Dunn, Hall, Harrison,\nHorrigan, Little, Parker (Flathead),\nSettle, Minnick.\nOn behalf of the many members of\nthe legislature who voted for this bill,\nit should be said that they voted for\nthe measure with the understanding it\nwas necessary to protect injured work\ners from the results of the Supreme\nCourt's decision on the Gugl\nBetween the time when the Supreme\nCourt, on February 23rd, gave its de\ncision on the Gugler case and the night\nof February 28th, when Senate Bill No.\n114, was enacted, some person or per\nsons were exceedingly busy spreading\npropaganda among the legislators to tlie\neffect that the decision of the Court\n111\ncase.\nf\nwould compel the Industrial Accident\nBoard to refuse to give medical atten\n\ntion or hospitalization to injured work\nerSt until such time as some one was\n\nsent by the Hoard to investigate the ac\ncident. therefore, the injured worker\nj. Hnrfnr\\ rare tmfil the\nwou,d hdve no floctor s cart timil tne\nIndustrial Accident Board had received\n'he report of the investigator ami <lc\n1\ncided that the injured worker was en\nt j t c( j 0 a doctor's attention and tot\nerr I\nprevent this state of affairs, it was nec\nessary to amend the Workmen's Com\ni r\npensation Act to clarify the court S de\ncisioil.\ngated this story before they considered\nh bi] j 0 in Holmes, State Auditor,\nThe legislators should have investi\nand Albert Kruse, Commissioner of\nAgriculture, Industry and Labor, both\nmembers of the Industrial Accident\nBoard knew nothing of the propoganda\nbeing spread among the members of\nthe legislature, neither were they con\nsulted with by the Chairman of the In\ndustrial Accident Board as to the ad\nvisability of amending the Compensa\ntion Act by Senate Bill No. 114.\nThe legislators could have enquired\nfrom the Attorney General or any judge\nof the Court if the Court's decision on\nthe Gugler case would prevent a victim\nof an Industrial Accident from getting\na doctor's attention or hospitalization.\nThe members of the legislature should\nnot have been so gullible as to swallow\nhook, bait and sinker, the propaganda\nthat was peddled them against the\nCourt on account of its decision in\nfavor of an injured worker.\nLabor Would Act Swiftly\nSuppose that Senate Bill No. 114 had\nnot been enacted and the Industrial Ac\ncident Board started to put into effect\ntile threat not to give the injured work\ners medical attention until the accident\nwas thoroughly investigated. Then or\nganized Labor would have acted in\nstantly. The Industrial Accident Board\n\nwould he snowed under by court ac\nthere might be a revolution in the In\ndustrial Accident Board and the Chair\nman find himself out of a job.\ntions, injunctions and Mandamus pro\nceeding, and possibly some employers\nwould experience work stoppages, a\nstrike, until the question of taking care\nof the wounded by industrial accidents\nwould have been settled. In the end\nThe Workmen's Compensation Act\nThis was not enacted for the benefit\nof doctors, or to give the Chairman of\nthe Board a job at $5,000 per year\u2014\nthe Compensation Act was enacted to\nmake industry take care of its injured\nthat they may not become a burden on\nthe general taxpayer.\nLook Out! Danger Ahead!\nThe enacting of legislation such as\nSenate Bill No. 114 in violation of the\nConstitution of the state, dm.ng the\nclosing hours of the legislature, estab\nlishes a precedent. Therefore, we need\nnot be surprised if some future sesssion\nof the legislature during the closing\nhours, and in violation of the Constitu\ntion enact a law making it a criminal\nconspiracy to belong to a labor union\nDUCK SEASON\nSEPT 20\nDuck Calls\nDuck Pants\nDuck Coats\nDuck Sox\nDuck Decoys\netc., etc., etc.\nPHIL JUDD'S\n83 E Park Street\n<S~\n\nDO YOU NEED MONEY?\n\n$5\u2014$25\u2014$60 OR MORE ON YOUR\nOWN NAME\nI\n\nI\nl\nMORRIS FINANCE CO.\n201 Lewisohn Building\n2nd Floor\n28 W. Granite St.\n\nThe Butte Independent\nPRINTERS\ni297 Harrison A?e.\n1,\nPHONE 6959\n\nBUY HOME PRODUCTS\nSILVER BOW BRAND\nHAMS BACON LARD\nY\n\u2022i\ny\n\u25a0o\nt\nHANSEN PACKING CO.\n\n\n\nButte, Montaiia\n\u00ef\nSAFE W A Y\nKERR JARS\nRegular Quarts\nDozen 85c\nKERR JARS\nRegular Puts\nDozen 69c\nKERR REGULAR LIDS\nDozen 10c\nKERR WIDE MOUTH LIDS\nDozen 15c\nJELLY GLASSES\nSquat or Tall\nDozen 39c\nPARAFFIN WAX\nLb. Carton 13c\nWIDE MOUTH JARS\nKerr Quarts\nDozen 99c\nJAR RUBBERS\nTop Seal or Shoulder\n5c\nor, enact a law to make business agents\npay one thousand dollars a year for a\nlicense to do business, or enact any\nother legislation to put labor unions and\nfraternal societies out of existence.\nThese things are possible\u2014What do\nyou think about it? What shall we do\nabout it?\nSenate Committee on Workmen's\nCompensation\u2014W a 11 a c e, Chairman\nAronson, Robinson, Lynch and Baker.\nWallace is said to be the author of\nSenate Bill No. 114.\nHouse Committee on Workmens\nCompensation\u2014Oliver^ Chairman; Sco\nfield, Rasmussen, Martin, Hazelhaker,\nMcGreevey, M innick, Gebhardt, Foot,\nFallen, Lehrkind, Dallas, Toole, Blew\nett, Christy.\nI\nJOHNSON BAR\ni\ni\n57 East Park St.\nPINE BEER, WINE AND LIQUORS\nYour Favorite Mixed Drinks\nLLOYD HAMILTON\nI\nI\n\nx\n\n\n\u00cf\nt\nx\nPrepare for a Cold\nWinter with a\nSYMONS 1945\nSmartly Styled\nFUR COAT\nLiberal Terms\nSymons Fur Dept.\n\n\n\ni\ni\n\n\n\n\nX\nI\n\n2\nX\n1\n\ni\n\nAak Tour Grocsr For\n\n\nnow\u00ab PBODOCV\nAMERICAN CRYSTAL\nSUGAR CO.","height":"20553","width":"14760"}}
